<Document>
<name>Tasmania East Coast</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Tasmania East Coast</h2><p><i>Tasmania, Australia · A3, Hobart to Bay of Fires via Freycinet and Bicheno</i></p><p><b>330 km of granite headlands, white sand, oyster bays, and orange-lichened boulders.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>235 km (146 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 3–4 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>December–April; year-round drivable but coldest July–August</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Wallabies and wombats on road at dawn/dusk (a real collision risk); narrow shoulders; queues for Wineglass Bay parking in summer</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>336</td></tr></table><hr><p>The east coast is Tasmania's sunniest and warmest — a string of granite headlands, oyster-farmed bays, and beaches where the sand squeaks underfoot. Freycinet Peninsula is the centerpiece: the Hazards (pink-granite peaks rising from the sea) and Wineglass Bay, regularly listed among the world's best beaches. Further north, Bay of Fires takes its name not from any literal fire but from cooking fires of the palawa (Tasmanian Aboriginal) people the European Tobias Furneaux saw burning along the coast in 1773; the orange color of the granite boulders is a coincidence of lichen. The whole coast is a stop on the Tasmanian oyster trail — buy a dozen at the farm gate, a lemon at the local store.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Maria Island</b> — Car-free national park reached by a 30-minute ferry from Triabunna. Wombats, Cape Barren geese, and Tasmanian devils (introduced as insurance population). The painted cliffs are sandstone stained by iron-rich groundwater into abstract patterns.</li><li><b>Spiky Bridge</b> — 1843 convict-built bridge with vertical stones cemented along the parapets — purpose disputed (to keep cattle from leaping over? to deter highwaymen?). 5-minute walk from the highway.</li><li><b>Swansea / Kate's Berry Farm</b> — Oldest east-coast town (1820s). The Hazards across Great Oyster Bay form the postcard. Kate's just south does berry sorbets that are worth a stop on their own.</li><li><b>Wineglass Bay</b> — Steep 1.5 km climb to the lookout; another 1 km steep descent to the beach itself if you want sand under your toes. Better still: 11 km circuit including Hazards Beach.</li><li><b>Bicheno</b> — Granite headland town where little (fairy) penguins come ashore at dusk year-round. Guided tours from the Bicheno Penguin Tours office (booking essential).</li><li><b>Bay of Fires</b> — 30 km of beaches between St Helens and Eddystone Point, broken by orange-lichened granite boulders piled in the surf zone. Camping at Cosy Corner, Swimcart, Sloop Reef. Bring shoes; no facilities.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
